{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":36172,"record_hash":"sha256:e81d8bbfa58c5bc3d565a068fed4f94d9a9abc3072ef4e9b4be8dfb02aa29012","timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:31:15.582Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yeah, this is the part where the system can start lying if we make the edge too precise too early.\n\nI’d separate two questions:\n\n1. **What do we attach?**  \n   Start by attaching the **whole session** to the change/commit/PR object.\n\n2. **What do we show?**  \n   Later, the UI can select or rank the most relevant transcript window.\n\nTrying to persist exact transcript slices now feels brittle. A long session can have planning, unrelated debugging, discarded attempts, and several branches worth of work. If we store “records 120-180 caused commit X,” we are pretending to know more than we do.\n\n**Better First Model**\nStore a coarse but honest edge:\n\n```text\nchange-id X\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = { session A }\n```\n\nMeaning:\n\n```text\nsession A is relevant context for change X\n```\n\nNot:\n\n```text\nevery line in session A produced change X\n```\n\nThen later, for review UI, we can derive a likely relevant slice by file/tool/timestamp overlap without making that derivation the durable truth.\n\n**Long Sessions**\nFor long sessions, whole-session association is still useful, but consumers should not dump the entire transcript by default. A future viewer can do:\n\n- show session summary\n- highlight messages near the commit time\n- highlight tool calls touching files in the change\n- allow “expand full session”\n- maybe show “this is a long session; filtered to likely relevant records”\n\nSo the durable association stays simple, while the presentation can be smarter.\n\n**Mutation Problem**\nYou’re right that commit lifecycle operations make this brittle if the edge is attached to the wrong thing.\n\nI’d model it like this:\n\n```text\nsession -> durable project session\n\nchange-id -> session set\ncommit -> derives from change-id when possible\nbranch/PR -> union of contained changes/commits\n```\n\nThen GitButler operations should preserve or move the relationship as part of their normal change lineage:\n\n- **Amend:** same change id, keep existing session edge. Add a new session edge if the amend was agent-assisted.\n- **Rebase:** same change id, commit hash changes, relationship survives.\n- **Uncommit:** if the change ceases to exist, the edge becomes unused/orphaned and should not show in branch/PR views.\n- **Recommit with same change id:** edge naturally comes back.\n- **Move/split hunks:** if GitButler knows hunks moved from change A to B, copy or move session edges accordingly.\n- **Squash:** destination change id survives, so union source session edges into destination.\n\nYour squash example is important: if a large AI change is squashed into a tiny manual destination commit, the destination should inherit the AI session edge. Otherwise the review UI loses the provenance exactly when it matters.\n\n**Avoid Overclaiming**\nThe edge should probably have a weak semantic name in our heads:\n\n```text\nrelated agent sessions\n```\n\nnot:\n\n```text\ngenerated by\n```\n\nThat lets us tolerate imperfect history edits. A session can be relevant even if only part of it contributed.\n\n**Pragmatic Path**\nI’d do this in phases:\n\n1. Keep capture project-scoped only.\n2. On GitButler commit/amend, associate recent/high-confidence session(s) to the change id.\n3. On squash/move operations, union/carry session edges along with the affected change lineage.\n4. Branch/PR pages read associations from the contained changes/commits, not from “current branch at capture time.”\n5. Only later add transcript slicing as computed UI behavior, not persisted source-of-truth.\n\nThat gives us a robust many-to-many graph without making us solve perfect causality.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:31:15.582Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}